pe":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Achard, II was born about 1255, in Aldermaston, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Peter Achard, was 27 and his mother, Isabel Englefield, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1294, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"ca. 1255–1294 ":"umbes 1255–1294","1255–1294":"1255–1294","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1230–1278":"1230–1278","1226–1299":"1226–1299","1226":"1226","1278 ":"1278","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1255":"1255","ca. 1255":"umbes 1255","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1260":"1260","1294 ":"1294","Aldermaston, Berkshire, England":"Aldermaston, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ca. 1255–1294 ":"noin 1255–1294","1255–1294":"1255–1294","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1293–Female":"1293–Kuollut","1230–1278":"1230–1278","1226–1299":"1226–1299","1226":"1226","1278 ":"1278","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1255":"1255","ca. 1255":"noin 12